# How much posterior probability lies above p = 0.8?
print(f"the probablity of posterior above p = 0.8 is {sum(samples > 0.8)/len(samples)}")

# How much posterior probability lies between p = 0.2 and p = 0.8?
print(f"the probability of posterior between p = 0.2 and p = 0.8 is {sum(np.logical_and(samples > 0.2, samples < 0.8))/len(samples)}")

# 20% of the posterior probability lies below which value of p?
samples.sort()
print(f"the value of p which 20% of the posterior probability lies below is {samples[int(len(samples)*0.2)]}")

# 20% of the posterior probability lies above which values of p?
print(f"The value of p which 20% of the posterior probability lies abvoe is {samples[int(len(samples)*0.8)]}")

# Which values of p contains the narrowest interval equal to 66% of the posterior probability?
interval_idx_inc = int(len(samples)*0.66)
n_intervals = len(samples)-interval_idx_inc
intervals = np.subtract(samples[interval_idx_inc:], samples[:n_intervals])
i = np.argmin(intervals)
lower, upper = samples[i], samples[i+interval_idx_inc]
print(f"p values between {lower} and {upper} is the narrowest interval equal to 66% of the posterior probability.")

print(f"p values between {lower} and {upper} has equal posterior probability both below and above the interval")

#3M3. Construct a posterior predictive check for this model and data. This means simulate the distribution of samples, averaging over the posterior uncertainty in p. What is the probability of observing 8 water in 15 tosses?
predictive = sp.stats.binom(15, samples).rvs()
unique_predictive = np.unique(predictive)
ax = sns.histplot(predictive, bins=unique_predictive+0.5);
ax.axvline(8, linestyle="dotted", color="red", label="8")
ax.set_title("Posterior Predictive Check")
print(f"The probability of 8 water in 15 tosses is {(predictive==8).mean()}")

# 3M6

# Analytic approach
# approximate with Normal distribution
# beta * bernouii ~ beta

def get_width(n):
    # generate data
    p_true = 0.7
    w = np.random.binomial(n=n, p=p_true)
    # get posterior
    p_grid = np.linspace(0, 1, num=1000)
    prior = np.repeat(1, 1000)
    prob_data = sp.stats.binom(n=n, p=p_grid).pmf(w)
    posterior = prob_data*prior
    posterior = posterior/sum(posterior)
    # get HDPI
    ci_p = 0.99
    size = 10000
    i_interval = int(size*ci_p)
    n_intervals = size-i_interval
    samples = np.random.choice(p_grid, p=posterior, size=size, replace=True)
    samples.sort()
    intervals = samples[i_interval:]-samples[:n_intervals]
    i_min = np.argmin(intervals)
    j_min = i_min + i_interval
    return (samples[j_min] - samples[i_min])
# 3M6 # Analytic approach # approximate with Normal distribution # beta * bernouii ~ beta def get_width(n): # generate data p_true = 0.7 w = np.random.binomial(n=n, p=p_true) # get posterior p_grid = np.linspace(0, 1, num=1000) prior = np.repeat(1, 1000) prob_data = sp.stats.binom(n=n, p=p_grid).pmf(w) posterior = prob_data*prior posterior = posterior/sum(posterior) # get HDPI ci_p = 0.99 size = 10000 i_interval = int(size*ci_p) n_intervals = size-i_interval samples = np.random.choice(p_grid, p=posterior, size=size, replace=True) samples.sort() intervals = samples[i_interval:]-samples[:n_intervals] i_min = np.argmin(intervals) j_min = i_min + i_interval return (samples[j_min] - samples[i_min])

n_ptrials = 10000
def get_HDPI(samples:np.array, p):
    """
    param samples: np.array of samples draw from the distribution
    param p: probability of Interval
    """
    n = len(samples)
    samples.sort()
    i_interval = int(n*p)
    n_intervals = n - i_interval
    intervals = samples[i_interval:] - samples[:n_intervals]
    i_min = np.argmin(intervals)
    j_min = i_min + i_interval
    return samples[i_min], samples[j_min]
n_ptrials = 10000 def get_HDPI(samples:np.array, p): """ param samples: np.array of samples draw from the distribution param p: probability of Interval """ n = len(samples) samples.sort() i_interval = int(n*p) n_intervals = n - i_interval intervals = samples[i_interval:] - samples[:n_intervals] i_min = np.argmin(intervals) j_min = i_min + i_interval return samples[i_min], samples[j_min]

Question: Use rbinom() to simulate 10000 replicates of 200 births. You should end up with 10000 numbers, each one a count of boys out of 200 births. Compare the distribution of predicted numbers of boys to the actual count in the data (111 boys out of 200 births). There are many good ways to visualize the simulations, but the dens() command (part of the rethinking package) is probably the easiest way in this case. Does it look like the model fits the data well? That is, does the distribution of predictions include the actual observation as a central, likely outcome?
